\h2{Motivation}

In terms of utility,
\tcode{std::big_int} has two main use case:
\ol{
  \li{
    The use case where integers are \dfn{potentially big}.
    For example,
    \tcode{std::big_int} could be the result of parsing an integer in a config file,
    and while the numbers are likely small in practice,
    it is \em{theoretically} possible that the user puts a huge value into the config file.
    \tcode{std::big_int} is useful in many scenarios because it eliminates the need
    for range checks,
    and it eliminates the possibility of undefined behavior through signed integer overflow.
    One could also describe this as the \q{correctness use case}.
  }
  \li{
    The use case where integers are \dfn{actually big}.
    For example, when performing computations in cryptography, statistics, etc.
    where the numbers involved simply don't fit into 64-bit integers.
  }
}

\h3{\tcode{std::big_int} is a vocabulary type}

An important reason why \tcode{std::big_int} should be in the C++ standard library
is that it is a vocabulary type and may appear at library boundaries.

\Bex{
A single code base may depend on different libraries that all interact with \tcode{std::big_int}:
\ol{
  \li{
    A library that loads config files (JSON, YAML, etc.)
    can return deserialized integers as \tcode{std::big_int}.
  }
  \li{
    Those \tcode{std::big_int} objects are then processed by a numeric library
    that uses them in e.g. statistics.
  }
  \li{
    The results are then stored by another library that serializes \tcode{std:big_int}
    to e.g. CSV.
  }
}
}

In some sense,
\tcode{std::big_int} is an even more important vocabulary type
than \tcode{std::vector} and \tcode{std::string}
because there is no convenient fallback solution.
If those containers were not available,
users could still communicate at library boundaries by using pointers and sizes.
Strings can be passed to other libraries as a \tcode{char*} (and maybe \tcode{size_t}),
so while \tcode{std::string} is an important container type,
it is arguably gratuitous as a vocabulary type.
By comparison,
there is no widely established convention for passing large integers between libraries in C++,
and \tcode{std::big_int} could lay that foundation.

\Bnote{
Sometimes (such as in the case of loading JSON configs),
large integers can be passed as decimal digit strings.
However, this is really just a form of delaying deserialization
in hopes that the library consumer can do it.

It is not a good way of passing huge integers between libraries in general
because conversion to/from strings for huge integers is very expensive.
}

\h3{\tcode{std::big_int} for convenience and correctness}

Another reason why \tcode{std::big_int} needs to be in the standard library
is that users would often avoid it otherwise,
even when it is the right tool for the job.
For example, it could be quite plausible that a library has to handle integers
with more than 64 bits in some edge cases,
but if the library author needs to add a dependency on the whole of Boost.Multiprecision
to replace 2-3 lines of code using \tcode{std::intmax_t} with \tcode{boost::cpp_int},
they may just not do it.

C++ developers don't get to choose between
a fixed-width type for performance and an infinite-precision type for correctness;
they get to choose between a fixed-width type
and adding a massive dependency for correctness,
which they may not do,
\em{especially} if that dependency is transitively forced onto their library users.

\h3{\tcode{std::big_int} is platform-dependent and hard to implement}

Another reason why \tcode{std::big_int} needs to be in the standard library
is that it's extremely difficult to implement and optimize,
in part because the implementation depends heavily on the platform's hardware capabilities,
many of which are not exposed portably in the language.

\Bex{
Some examples of platform and compiler-specific features:
\ul{
  \li{
    x86_64 has a \tt{mul} instruction that yields
    both the low and the high bits of a multiplication;
    without utilizing that,
    multiprecision multiplication is much slower.
  }
  \li{
    x86_64 also has a \tt{div} instruction that takes a 128-bit dividend and a 64-bit divisor,
    which can be used to implement division of an arbitrary-length dividend much more efficiently.
  }
  \li{
    Funnel-shifting (basically a 128-bit shift)
    is a common operation in multiprecision arithmetic,
    and Clang recently got a \tcode{__builtin_elementwise_funnel_shl} intrinsics that exposes
    the hardware instruction.
  }
  \li{
    Bitwise operations between \tcode{std::big_int}
    can be performed in parallel using SIMD intrinsics.
    While those can be portably implemented using \header{simd} now,
    that may add unnecessary overhead compared to using the underlying intrinsics directly.
  }
  \li{
    Conversions between \tcode{std::big_int} and floating-point types may be
    hardware-accelerated or backed by special routines in the runtime library.
    For example, to convert \tcode{float} to \tcode{std::big_int},
    the conversion should go through \tcode{__fixunssfti}
    (\tcode{float} \'RIGHTWARDS ARROW' \tcode{unsigned __int128})
    followed by a conversion to \tcode{std::big_int}.
    Note that an unsigned 128-bit integer is sufficient to represent any finite
    binary32 floating-point number without the fractional part.
  }
  \li{
    During constant evaluation,
    if \tcode{_BitInt} is available,
    it is often faster to implement an operation in terms of \tcode{_BitInt}.
    For example, a 4096-bit division can be delegated entirely to compiler intrinsics
    by converting the dividend and divisor to \tcode{_BitInt(4096)},
    performing the division in terms of e.g. \tcode{llvm::APInt} operations.
    This completely avoids the need for constant evaluation of complex division routines.
  }
}
}

In general, the intrinsics necessary to implement \tcode{std::big_int} efficiently
vary wildly from compiler to compiler
and from architecture to architecture.
It also varies a lot whether those intrinsics can be used during constant evaluation,
and these implementation details are subject to frequent change and added features.
Our \ref("Reference-Impl") of \tcode{std::big_int} is a sea of \tcode{if constexpr}
and \tcode{#ifdef} checks.

Overall, it is practically impossible or at least extremely difficult for a third-party library
to keep up with all these details to implement the type optimally,
across all compilers and all supported architectures.
Features like these should ideally live directly in the compiler or in the standard library.

\h3{\tcode{std::big_int} should be a compiler intrinsic for constant evaluation}

While a portable implementation of \tcode{std::big_int} is possible,
an ideal implementation for constant evaluation simply delegates
to the compiler's internal infinite-precision integer type (e.g. \tcode{llvm::APInt} in LLVM).
This is because constant evaluation is relatively expensive
compared to highly optimized multiprecision code in the compiler internals.
A third-party library such as Boost.Multiprecision
does not have the luxury of adding new compiler intrinsics,
so the implementation quality could never match the potential of \tcode{std::big_int}.

A closely related issue is the implementation of the user-defined literal,
which has the following interface in our proposal:
\cppblock{
template<char... digits>
  constexpr big_int operator""n();

// now possible:
big_int x = 123'456'789'012'345'678'901'234'567'890n;
}

The problem is that there is no other form of \tcode{operator""n}
that provides the obvious syntax,
and the \tcode{char...} form requires manual parsing of the digits during constant evaluation,
rather than delegating this to the compiler.
It would be much better if parsing could be done in the compiler to provide a form such as:
\cppblock{
constexpr big_int operator""n(const uint_multiprecision_t* limbs, size_t size);
}

With this form,
\ul{
  \li{digit separators would be skipped automatically,}
  \li{base prefixes like \tcode{0x} would be handled by the compiler, and}
  \li{forming the limb array would be done by the compiler, which is the expensive part,}
  \li{template instantiations would be avoided completely.}
}

That being said,
this new form of \tcode{operator""n"} is not part if this proposal,
but it does demonstrate why some compiler support is needed.

\h2{Design}

The most important anchor points of the design are:

\ul{
  \li{
    \tcode{std::big_int} should be elastic;
    that is, it should grow to the necessary size required to fit the result
    of an arithmetic operation
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{std::big_int} should support custom allocators
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{std::big_int} should expose \q{small object optimization} to the user
  }
}

This culminates in the following library declarations:

\cppblock{
// Class template:
template<size_t min_inplace_capacity, class Allocator = allocator<uint_multiprecision_t>>
  class basic_big_int;

// Alias with default in-place capacity and default allocator
using big_int = basic_big_int<\i{implementation-defined capacity}>;
}

Conceptually, a \tcode{basic_big_int} holds:
\cppblock{
union {
  // In-place representation, used for small values:
  uint_multiprecision_t inplace_storage[N];
  // Dynamic representation, used for large values:
  struct {
    uint_multiprecision_t* dynamic_storage;
    size_t dynamic_capacity;
  };
};
}

The underlying arithmetic is then implemented to operate on \dfn{limb arrays},
i.e. arrays of \tcode{uint_multiprecision_t} objects,
agnostic of whether the integer value is store in-place or dynamically.

\h3{\tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t}}

A user-facing integer type alias introduced by this paper is \tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t},
which is an unsigned integer type with the following important properties:
\ul{
  \li{
    \tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t} has no padding bits.
    Padding bits in a limb type would be wasteful and make things more difficult both
    for users and for implementations.
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t} is the widest type that has arithmetic hardware support.
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t} has no explicit minimum width,
    but effectively cannot be narrower than \tcode{unsigned char} due to being unpadded.
  }
}

In summary, it is the unsigned integer type most suitable for multiprecision.


Curiously, there is no existing type with the desired properties
despite the abundance of type aliases in \header{cstdint} and \header{cstddef}:
\ul{
  \li{
    \tcode{std::int_fast32_t} is at least 32 bits wide,
    which means that on 16-bit architectures,
    the multiprecision code would have two layers:
    the emulation of 32-bit integers on 16-bit hardware,
    and then the multiprecision of \tcode{std::big_int} operations.
    This is highly questionable because the point of \tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t}
    is to have a type whose operations correspond directly to hardware instructions.
    Also, \tcode{std::int_fast32_t} is not consistently 64 bits wide on targets
    with 64-bit arithmetic support.
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{std::size_t} often could be used as \tcode{std::uint_multiprecision_t},
    but on targets like WASM32,
    it is only 32 bits wide despite WASM32 having 64-bit arithmetic instructions for \tt{i64}.
    It would be extremely wasteful to only use 32-bit operations when 64 bits are available.
  }
}

\h3{Small object optimizations}

\tcode{std::big_int} (or generally, infinite-precision integer types)
benefit from \dfn{small object optimization}
perhaps more than any other vocabulary type.
This is because with a relatively small amount of in-place storage
(e.g. 8 bytes for 64-bit numbers),
a lot of applications would \em{never} need to allocate dynamic storage to hold the value,
or only for extreme and unusual program inputs.
Furthermore,
once the numbers are huge enough to require dynamic allocation,
the cost of multiprecision arithmetic often hugely outweighs
the small amount of overhead caused by having a few unused bytes of in-place storage.

\Bnote{
By comparison,
all major standard libraries have small object optimization for \tcode{std::string},
but many strings exceed the in-place capacity (around 20 bytes),
so dynamic allocation for fairly short strings remains common.
}

The optimization is also necessary to prevent excessive allocations for small intermediate results.
For example, even for huge inputs \tcode{x} and \tcode{y},
the difference \tcode{x - y}, the quotient \tcode{x / y},
or the remainder \tcode{x % y} could still be fairly small numbers (possibly zero),
and it is wasteful to dynamically allocate for tiny integers.

Because performing this optimization for \tcode{std::big_int} is such a no-brainer
and any reasonable implementation should have it,
we propose to expose it to the user via the \tcode{min_inplace_capacity} template parameter.
This parameter specifies the minimum integer width that \tcode{std::basic_big_int}
must be able to represent without dynamic allocation.
While \tcode{std::big_int} should be used in most cases and provides a reasonable default,
there may be scenarios where
\ul{
  \li{
    on 32-bit platforms, the capacity could be lowered to \tcode{32} or raised to \tcode{64}
    to prefer performance or correctness,
  }
  \li{
    on platforms where allocations are particularly expensive
    or where dynamic storage is very limited,
    the capacity could be raised to \tcode{128} or even \tcode{256}.
  }
}

\Bnote{
In our \ref("Reference-Impl"),
\tcode{std::big_int::inplace_capacity} is always 64 regardless of architecture.
On 64-bit, our layout is as follows:
\cppblock{
// Most significant bit stores the sign;
// the lower 31 bis store the limb count.
uint32_t size_and_sign;
// The capacity of the dynamic storage in limbs.
// If zero, indicates that there is no allocation and that inplace_storage is active.
uint32_t capacity;
union {
  // For values up to 64 bits.
  // For big_int, N = 1, but the min_inplace_capacity parameter allows more capacity
  // for other basic_big_int specializations.
  uint64_t inplace_storage[N];
  // For anything that doesn't fit into inplace_storage.
  uint64_t* dynamic_storage;
};
}

This layout ensures that \tcode{std::big_int}
\ul{
  \li{is two pointers large,}
  \li{is aligned to one pointer,}
  \li{is nothrow-movable and trivially relocatable,}
  \li{can represent both \tcode{int64_t} and \tcode{uint64_t} values without allocating, and}
  \li{
    can represent values with up to \math{\msup{\mn{2}\mrow{\mn{31}\mo{+}\mn{6}}}} bits
    (137 billion bits).
  }
}
}

\h3{Sign and magnitude}

\tcode{std::big_int} uses a sign-and-magnitude representation
(as opposed to e.g. two's complement),
and this is exposed to the user.
While it may seem like constraining implementation freedom unnecessarily,
the chosen representation impacts the complexity requirements of various operations.
For example, if the sign bit is separately stored,
then negation can be implemented in constant time by just flipping the sign bit,
whereas for two's complement,
it requires linear time because bits of the magnitude need updating.

Most implementations of infinite-precision integers use sign-and-magnitude representation,
as does our \ref("Reference-Impl").
This is not only due to those beneficial complexity requirements,
but also because it simplifies the implementation greatly.
For example:
multiplicative operators like multiplication and division can be implemented
solely in terms of the magnitude,
and the sign bit of the result can be computed separately.

The only major downside of sign-and-magnitude representation is that it requires
emulation of two's complement for bitwise operations,
but this is relatively cheap and does not require an additional pass over the data.
That is, for example, to compute \tcode{a & b} with negative inputs,
the implementation negates the limbs of negative inputs on the fly
and also negates the final result if the result is negative.

\Bnote{
\tcode{~x} is equivalent to \tcode{(-x - 1)}.
In bitwise operations,
negative inputs are treated as if they were preceded by an infinite sequences of leading ones, and
positive inputs are treated as if they were preceded by an infinite sequence of leading zeros.
}

\h3{Naming}

The name \tcode{std::big_int} was chosen because it meets user expectations
and makes its design instantly clear.
In languages where infinite-precision integers are not built-in,
the name is virtually always some variant of \q{big int} or \q{big integer}.
The name \tcode{std::big_int} is also immediately recognizable
as supporting infinite-precision arithmetic and as growing elastically as needed.

Previous proposals used the name \tcode{std::integer},
but this name doesn't convey the design well,
and is too similar to concept names like \tcode{std::integral}.

\h2{Implementation experience}

Our reference implementation can be found at \ref("Reference-Impl").

\h2{Wording}

The changes are relative to \ref("N5032").

